	        Send us your pictures   ·  Send us your stories The South African Weather Service (SAWS) has issued a severe weather watch warning of thundershowers over Gauteng, Mpumalanga, Limpopo and the North West on Wednesday. Satellite imagery shows a thick band of cloud over certain areas in the northern parts of SA. Temperatures in Gauteng are expected to peak at 30°C in Johannesburg on Wednesday and 25°C on Thursday. "Partly cloudy and warm with isolated showers and thundershowers, becoming cloudy from the south later," the SAWS said in its Gauteng forecast. In Nelspruit, the maximum temperature is expected to be 21°C, while it is expected to be 28°C in Emalahleni and Polokwane. Mahikeng is expected to reach a maximum of 30°C. Windy.com indicated thundershower activity over the northern parts of SA, centred around Pretoria, Polokwane, Groblersdal, Emalahleni and Daggakraal on Wednesday. A low pressure system of around 1 000 millibars appears to be driving the thunderstorm activity, which is set to subside by Thursday. The SAWS also issued a weather advisory for fog along the eastern escarpment of Limpopo and hot weather over the Western Bushveld. Good day! Kindly find media release below for the stormy weather and heavy rain expected for parts of South Africa from today (31/10/2018) until 01/11/2018. Do take care. pic.twitter.com/j42840UF0X  Warning:31/10/2018 11h00 TO:31/10/2018 14h00 Severe Thunderstorms- observed over Moloto/Kwa-Mhlanga area moving E towards the Groblersdal area, with large amounts of small hail, heavy downpours and damaging winds.  Warning:31/10/2018 12h00 TO:31/10/2018 13h00 Severe Thunderstorms- are expected over the Ermelo and Mkhondo in Mpumalanga.    KEEP UPDATED on the latest news by subscribing to our FREE newsletter. - FOLLOW News24 on Twitter 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  